# Debuggin in playwright

1️⃣ What is Debugging in Playwright?
Debugging in playwright means identifying and fixing issues in test scripts when test fail or behave unexpectedly.
It helps to:
    1. Understand why a test failed
    2. Inspect the browser using execution
    3. Analyze selectors , actions and assertions
Debugging tools allows you to pause , inspect elements , check logs and trace execution.

2️⃣ Why Debugging is Important in Playwright
Debugging helps in :
    1. Test fail unexpectedly
    2. Locators are correct
    3. Timing issue occur
    4. Elements are not visible or interactable
    5. Flaky tests appear

Benefits:
    1. Faster issue identification
    2. Easier test maintenance
    3. Reliable automation tests

3️⃣ Running Tests in Debug Mode
Playwright provides a debug mode that runs tests slowly and allows inspection.
Command:
    pytest --headed --slowmo=1000
Explanation:
    --headed -> open browser with UI
    --slowmo -> Adds delay (1000ms) between actions

Example:
    page.goto("https://example.com")
    page.click("text-login").click()
You can visually see each step happennig in the browser

4️⃣ Using page.pause() for Debugging
Playwright provides a pause method to stop test execution.
Example:
    page.goto("https://example.com")
    page.pause()
    page.click("text=login")
What happens:
    1. Test execution pauses
    2. Playwright inspector opens
    3. You can inspect elements and run commands

5️⃣ Playwright Inspector
Playwright inspector is a debugging GUI tool.
It helps you:
    1. sleep through tests
    2. Inspect locators
    3. Run commands manually
    4. Resum execution

Features:
    1. Highlight elements
    2. Evaluate selectors
    3. Step-by-Step execution
    4. Edit locators interactively

6️⃣ Using PWDEBUG Environment Variable
You can enable debugging using an evironmental variable.
Command:
    PWDDEBUG=1 pytest
This will:
    1. Launch the browser in debug mode
    2. Open playwright inspector
    3. Pause execution automatically
Useful for deep debugging

7️⃣ Debugging with Print Logs
Sometimes simple logs help identify issues.
Example:
    print("Navigating to login page")

    page.goto("https://example.com")

    print("Clicking login button")
    page.click("text=Login")

This helps track where the test fails.

8️⃣ Taking Screenshots for Debugging
Screenshots help capture the UI state when a test fails.
Example:
    page.screenshot(path = "screenshot.png")

Example with failure debuggin:
    try:
        page.click("#login")
    expect:
        page.screenshot(path="error.png")

Benefits:
    1. Visual proof of failure
    2. Easy Analysis

9️⃣ Recording Trace for Debugging
Playwright provides trace viewer for deep debuggin.
Trace includes:
    1. Screenshots
    2. DOM snapshots
    3. Network logs
    4. Console logs
Enable tracing:
    context.tracing.start(screenshots=True , snapshots = True)

    # run test scripts
    context.tracing.stop(path="trace.zip")
View trace:
    playwright show-trace trace.zip
Trace Viewer shows step-by-step execution of tests.

🔟 Using Video Recording
Playwright can record test execution videos.
Example:
    browser.new_context(record_video_dir="videos/")
Benefits:
    1. Watch test execution
    2. Identify UI failures
    3. Understand flaky tests

1️⃣1️⃣ Debugging Locators
Many failures happen due to incorrect locators.
Example:
    page.click("#login-btn")

Use locator debugging:
    locator=page.locator("#login-btn")
    print(locator.count())

This helps verify if the element exists.

1️⃣2️⃣ Using locator.highlight() (Inspector)
In playwright inspector , you can:
    1. Hover elements
    2. Highlight elements
    3. Check visibility
This helps confirm that the correct element is selected.

1️⃣3️⃣ Common Debugging Techniques
Best practices:
    1. Run tests in headed mode
    2. Use slow motion
    3. Use playwright inspector
    4. Take screenshots
    5. Record traces
    6. Add logs
    7. Verify locators

1️⃣4️⃣ Example Debugging Workflow
Example test:
    def test_login(page):

    page.goto("https://example.com")

    page.pause()

    page.fill("#username", "admin")
    page.fill("#password", "admin123")

    page.click("#login")

    assert page.locator("text=Dashboard").is_visible()

Steps:
    1. Test pauses at page.pause()
    2. Inspector opens
    3. Check elements
    4. Resume test
